      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How to Choose a Real Estate Agent in Brisbane: What Sellers Should Actually Look For
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Most sellers choose their agent using the wrong signals. Here is how to cut through the pitch and identify an agent who will actually produce a better result.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Choosing a real estate agent is one of the most consequential decisions you will make in a property sale. The difference between an agent who performs at the top of the market and one who is merely adequate can amount to tens of thousands of dollars on a comparable property in Brisbane's inner east. The problem is that most sellers choose their agent based on signals that have almost nothing to do with how well the agent will perform: which agency's board they see most often, who gave the highest price estimate at appraisal, or who had the most confident presentation.</p>

      <p>None of these is a reliable proxy for results. Understanding what to actually look for requires rethinking the entire appraisal process from the start.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The price estimate problem</h2>
      <p>The most common mistake sellers make is using the appraisal estimate as the primary filter for choosing an agent. The logic seems reasonable: if Agent A says your property is worth $1.4 million and Agent B says $1.2 million, then Agent A has greater confidence in your property and is probably better. This reasoning is exactly backwards.</p>

      <p>A practice called buying the listing is widespread in residential real estate. An agent deliberately inflates their initial price estimate to win the listing, knowing that once they have the signed authority, they can progressively lower your expectations over subsequent weeks as the property sits on market without offers at the inflated price. The agent knows you are unlikely to switch mid-campaign after you have already done photography, committed to marketing spend, and had buyers through. The result is usually a longer campaign, more price reductions, and a final sale price below what a properly priced campaign would have achieved from day one.</p>

      <p>The correct way to use an appraisal estimate is to compare it against actual recent comparable sales data, not against what other agents told you. If you can access sold data for properties genuinely comparable to yours in the past three to six months, you will have a far more reliable range than any agent can give you at an appraisal. Agents who give you a range closely anchored to the evidence, even when that evidence produces a less flattering number, are demonstrating exactly the honesty and market knowledge you want in a campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the agent's personal record actually tells you</h2>
      <p>Agency brand recognition is almost irrelevant to your outcome. What matters is the specific agent's personal sales record in your suburb and price bracket. Large offices have multiple agents, and the quality varies enormously within the same brand. Ask the agent you are meeting with how many properties they personally sold in your suburb in the past six months, what the final prices were relative to their initial price guidance, and what the days-on-market were for those campaigns.</p>

      <p>If an agent cannot give you specific answers to these questions, or deflects to the office's aggregate numbers, that is a meaningful red flag. An agent who has genuinely produced strong results in your area will want you to know about those results in detail. They will have the numbers available because they track them. An agent who is vague about their personal record either does not have a strong record in your suburb or is not paying enough attention to their own performance to be managing yours.</p>

      <p>Pay particular attention to days-on-market figures. In Brisbane's inner east, a well-priced, well-presented property in reasonable market conditions should generate serious interest within the first two to three weeks of campaign. An agent whose recent listings have been running for eight to twelve weeks before selling is either consistently mispricing, undermarketing, or working markets where their record does not apply to your suburb.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions that reveal how an agent actually works</h2>
      <p>The appraisal meeting is your opportunity to interview the agent. Most sellers treat it as the opposite, listening to the agent's pitch and responding to their questions. Shift the dynamic. The agent needs your listing; you need information about their performance. The following questions tend to separate agents who are strong operators from those who are strong presenters.</p>

      <p>Ask how many listings the agent is currently managing. An agent running twenty active campaigns simultaneously cannot give your sale the attention it needs. The right number depends on the individual, but anything above twelve to fifteen active listings for a single agent (not a team) should prompt follow-up questions about how they structure their time and how communication works during your campaign.</p>

      <p>Ask what method of sale they recommend for your property and why. A thoughtful answer will reference the current buyer profile for your property type, whether the suburb is performing better under auction clearance conditions or private treaty, and any specific characteristics of your property that suit one method over the other. A generic answer that defaults to auction without any property-specific reasoning is a sign that the agent is applying their preferred method rather than the right method for your situation.</p>

      <p>Ask how they handle the first week of a campaign if buyer interest is lower than expected. Strong agents have a clear process: they will give you data on inquiry numbers, open home attendance, and comparative interest from other campaigns, and they will have a view on whether the issue is pricing, presentation, or something else. Agents who respond with vague reassurance rather than data-backed assessment are telling you something important about how they communicate under pressure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The negotiation question most sellers forget to ask</h2>
      <p>The skill that most directly affects your final sale price is negotiation. Yet most sellers never ask about it. How an agent handles multiple offers, manages a buyer who makes a lowball offer, or maintains competitive tension between two interested parties during an auction or private treaty campaign is where the real difference in outcomes is made.</p>

      <p>Ask the agent to describe a recent negotiation they are proud of. Not a sale price, but the negotiation itself: how they created competition between buyers, how they handled a buyer who was resistant, what they did when a deal looked like it was about to fall over. An agent who can give you a specific, honest account of how they navigate those moments has actually navigated them. An agent who speaks in generalities about their negotiation style probably has not had to do it under real pressure recently.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Red flags in how agents present themselves</h2>
      <p>Some patterns in how agents pitch themselves at appraisal are reliably associated with worse outcomes for sellers. Watch for agents who focus heavily on their personal brand, awards, or media presence rather than on the specific evidence of how their campaigns have performed. Watch for agents who are dismissive of your property's challenges rather than honest about how they will address them in marketing and negotiation. Watch for agents who give you a very high appraisal without strong comparable sales evidence to support it.</p>

      <p>Also watch for agents who are visibly uncomfortable when you ask them specific questions about their sales record. A strong agent welcomes scrutiny. They have spent years building a record they are proud of, and they want you to see it. An agent who deflects, changes the subject, or gives vague answers to direct questions about their performance has answered your question, even if not directly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Rapport matters, but it is not enough</h2>
      <p>You will be communicating with this person frequently during a campaign that may last four to twelve weeks. You will be relying on their judgement during high-stakes negotiations. Personal rapport is a legitimate factor in choosing an agent. An agent you do not trust or feel comfortable being honest with will produce a worse outcome simply because the communication will be less effective.</p>

      <p>But rapport should be a tiebreaker, not the primary criterion. If two agents have comparable performance records and you find one considerably easier to work with, that is a meaningful difference. If one agent has a significantly stronger comparable sales record but you find them less warm, the record should win. In Brisbane's inner east, the financial difference between an agent who performs at 95% of market and one who performs at 100% of market is not marginal on a $1.5 million property.</p>

